Background¶

Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in E-news Express. The design team of the company has created a new landing page. You have been assigned the task to decide whether the new landing page is more effective to gather new subscribers. Suppose you randomly selected 100 users and divided them equally into two groups. The old landing page is served to the first group (control group) and the new landing page is served to the second group (treatment group).

Dataset File¶

abtest.csv

Dataset Columns¶

  1. user_id - This represents the user ID of the person visiting the website.
  2. group - This represents whether the user belongs to the first group (control) or the second group (treatment).
  3. landing_page - This represents whether the landing page is new or old.
  4. time_spent_on_the_page - This represents the time (in minutes) spent by the user on the landing page.
  5. converted - This represents whether the user gets converted to a subscriber of the news portal or not.
  6. language_preferred - This represents the language chosen by the user to view the landing page.

Questions¶

1. What's the result of exploratory data analysis?¶

  • Describe the initial dataset
  • Plot the univariate distributions and describe them
  • Plot the multivariate correlations and describe them

2. Do the users spend more time on the new landing page than the old landing page?¶

  • Satisfy Normal distributions?
  • Satisfy Equal variances/standard deviations?
  • Two Independent Sample T-test for Equality of Means - Equal Std Dev
  • One-Tailed
  • ttest_ind()

3. Is the conversion rate for the new page greater than the conversion rate for the old page?¶

  • Binomial
  • Two Proportion Z Test
  • One-Tailed
  • proportions_ztest()

4. Does the converted status depend on the preferred language?¶

  • Setup contingency table with pd.crosstab()
  • Chi Square Test for Independence
  • chi2_contingency()

5. Is the mean time spent on the new page same for the different language users?¶

  • check for normal distributions shapiro()
  • check for equal variances levene()
  • One Way ANOVA test
  • f_oneway()

*Consider a significance level of 0.05 (5%) for all tests¶

Question: Do the users spend more time on the new landing page than the old landing page?¶

We already determined through exploratory data analysis that, on average, users spend more time on the new landing page than the old landing page, but what is the probability that this increase in time is not because of random chance?

Null and Alternate Hypotheses for Testing Equality of Means¶

We will test the null hypothesis

$H_0:\mu_n=\mu_o$

against the alternate hypothesis

$H_a:\mu_n>\mu_o$

Check the assumptions¶

  • The data being tested is continous (time_spent_on_the_page)
  • The data being tested seems to be normally distributed
  • The two samples being tested are independent
  • The data was collected randomly from the population
  • The standard deviations of the samples are close enough to be assumed equal
    • 2.6 is not more than 2 times 1.8
  • This is a one-tailed test

Therefore we will use the Two Independent Sample T-test ttest_ind()¶

In [27]:
test_stat, p_value = stats.ttest_ind(
    new['time_spent_on_the_page'],       # treatment
    old['time_spent_on_the_page'],       # control
    equal_var = True,                    # equal by assumption
    alternative = 'greater')             # greater because this is a one-tailed test
print('The p-value is ' + str(p_value))

The p-value is 0.0001316123528095005

Observations¶

The probability that these 2 samples came from populations with equal means is 0.01%. Since this is well below our confidence level of 5%, we reject the null hypothesis.

Thus, we can say with 95% confidence that the time spent on the new landing page is greater than the time spent on the old page.¶

Question: Is the conversion rate for the new page greater than the conversion rate for the old page?¶

We already determined through exploratory data analysis that the conversion rate for the new page was greather, but is this statistically significant? Do we have enough data from our samples to say the increase in conversions is not due to random chance?

Null and Alternate Hypotheses for Testing Equality of Proportions¶

We will test the null hypothesis

$H_0:p_n =p_o$

against the alternate hypothesis

$H_a:p_n > p_o$

Check the assumptions¶

  • The data being tested is discrete (converted)
  • The data is binomial (yes or no)
  • The binomial distribution can be approximated to the Normal distribution because of the Central Limit Theorem
  • The two samples being tested are independent
  • The data was collected randomly from the population
  • The samples are greater than 30 (n=50)
  • The proportion values within those samples are greather than 10
  • This is a one-tailed test

Therefore we will use the Two Proportion Z Test proportions_ztest()¶

In [28]:
# set the counts of successful conversions [new, old]
yes_count = np.array([33, 21])

# set the sample sizes
n = np.array([50, 50])

# find the p-value, set alternative to larger because this is a one-sided test
test_stat, p_value = proportions_ztest(yes_count, n, alternative='larger')
print('The p-value is ' + str(p_value))

The p-value is 0.008026308204056278

Observations¶

The probability that these two samples came from populations with equal proportions is 0.8%. Since this is well below our confidence level of 5%, we reject the null hypothesis.

Thus we can extrapolate, with 95% confidence, that the conversion rate for users on the new page is greather than the conversion page of the old page.¶

Question: Does the converted status depend on the preferred language?¶

We already determined through exploratory data analysis earlier that, out of the 3 language preferences, those who chose English had the highest rate of conversion. But does this difference represent a significant correlation? What is the probability that this observed variation is not just random chance? Do we have statistical evidence to conclude converted status depends on preferred language?

Null and Alternate Hypotheses for Testing Independence¶

$H_0:$ Conversion status is independent of preferred language

$H_a:$ Converstion status depends on preferred language

Check the Assumptions¶

  • Three independent categorical variables (discrete) against proportion (discrete)
  • The data was collected randomly from the population
  • At least 5 values in each level of the sample
  • Construction of a contingency table
  • Chi Square Distribution

Therefore we will use Chi Square Test for Independence chi2_contingency()¶

In [29]:
# Create a contingency table
table = pd.crosstab(df['converted'],df['language_preferred'])
table
Out[29]:
language_preferred English French Spanish
converted
no 11 19 16
yes 21 15 18
In [30]:
# Run the Chi Square test on the contingency table
chi, p_value, dof, expected = stats.chi2_contingency(table)
print('The p-value is', p_value)

The p-value is 0.21298887487543447

Observations¶

From the model used, there is a 21% chance that the data in these samples came from a population where conversion status is independent of preferred language. Since the probability is much higher than our significance level of 5%, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.

Thus, we conclude with 95% confidence that conversion status is independent of preferred language. There is not enough evidence in the samples to state that language preference has an influence on conversion status.¶

Question: Is the mean time spent on the new page same for the different language users?¶

We have already determined through exploratory data analysis that the mean times spent on the new page are nearly the same for the different languge users in the samples.

English 6.7; French 6.2; Spanish 5.8

Can we infer that the population's average time spent on the page is also the same for different language users?

Null and Alternate Hypotheses for Testing Variance of 2+ Means¶

Let $\mu_1, \mu_2, \mu_3$ be the means of time spent on page for preferred languages English, French, and Spanish respectively.

$H_0: \mu_1 = \mu_2 = \mu_3$

$H_a: $ At least one mean is different

Check Assumptions¶

  • The data was collected in simple random samples
  • The data being tested seems to be normally distributed
  • Population variances are equal

Therefore we will perform a One Way ANOVA Test f_oneway()¶

In [31]:
# First, double-check that the data is normally distributed with the shapiro() test

w1, p1_value = stats.shapiro(new['time_spent_on_the_page']) 
print('The p-value for the control is', p1_value)

The p-value for the control is 0.8040016293525696

The check passed and we can assume the time values are Normal.

In [32]:
# Second, double-check that the population variances are equal with the levene() test

statistic, p_value = stats.levene( new['time_spent_on_the_page'][new['language_preferred']=='English'], 
                                   new['time_spent_on_the_page'][new['language_preferred']=='French'], 
                                   new['time_spent_on_the_page'][new['language_preferred']=='Spanish'])
# find the p-value
print('The p-value is', p_value)

The p-value is 0.46711357711340173

The check passed and we can assume the population variances are equal.

In [33]:
# Finally, test the means with the f_oneway() test

test_stat, p_value = stats.f_oneway(new.loc[new['language_preferred'] == 'English', 'time_spent_on_the_page'],
                              new.loc[new['language_preferred'] == 'French', 'time_spent_on_the_page'],
                              new.loc[new['language_preferred'] == 'Spanish', 'time_spent_on_the_page'])
print('The p-value is ' + str(p_value))

The p-value is 0.43204138694325955

Observations¶

The probability that the time spent on the new page was the same for all three language preferences is 43%. Since this is far above our confidence level of 5%, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.

Thus we conclude with 95% confidence that the time spent on the new page is the same for all languages. There is enough statistical evidence to say that the new landing page is engaging users of different languages for equal amounts of time.¶
